Danielson Against other Metrics

Comparing the metrics

In this piece, weâll start comparing across different metrics of teacher success.

  • The Disposition score of the studentâs most important college class (modified using the same z-score method as Danielson)
  • Whether or not they received Idaho teacher certification
  • How well the student did on their Praxis exams relative to their peers (not just if they passed, but by what margin)
  • Surveys from the principal, evaluating that studentâs effectiveness in the classroom as a teacher
  • Surveys from the student themselves with the same questions.
Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(arrow)

         employer_survey_total,self_survey_total)

all %>%
  arrange(self_survey_total) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  head(5) %>%
  pander()

Danielson & Z-Score

This analysis builds off the aggregation of Danielson observations recorded in this article.
In summary, weâve condensed down the Danielson observations across dozens of classes and individual reports based on three criteria:

  1. Weâve prioritized observations from the classes furthest along in the studentâs career. For most students, we use their scores from ED 492, but for those missing observations, we use any other 400-level, then 300- and 200-level class.
  2. If a student has more than one observation recorded for the class, we prioritize the summative evaluations over the formative ones.
  3. To compensate for different grading standards across teachers, weâve turned each raw final score (a 3-pt scale of 22 questions) into a z_score. Now each score reflects how the student did in this class compared to their peers.-

\[ zscore = \frac{x_{StudentScore} - \mu_{TeacherAndSemester}}{\sigma_{TeacherAndSemester}} \] After these steps, we go from 9854 individual observations to 1776 values tied to student records.

Unfortunately, only 23 of our 1776 potential teachers received all 6 of these summative evaluations. As a result, each of these smaller analysis will use different sub-sections of these 1776 students.

Itâs important to notice that because we made all these adjustments from the raw observations, this analysis wonât be useful for predicting individual scores. This can only tell which other metrics are most likely to help students succeed.

Danielson against Disposition

These two features have a strong positive relationship. Many of these students were tested by the same teacher for both types of evaluation, so the correlation may be influenced by the same source.

Code 
lm_dan_disp <- lm(WDanielson_highest_level ~ Disposition_highest_level, data = all)

all_metrics <- drop_na(all) #now only the people with all metrics
dan_all <- lm(WDanielson_highest_level~Disposition_highest_level+certification+Prax_avg_zscore+self_survey_total+employer_survey_total,data=all_metrics)
summary(dan_all) %>% pander()

Certification disappears because all of these students were certified. Code 
intercepts = tibble('Factor'=c('Intercept','Disposition_highest_level','certification','Prax_avg_zscore','self_survey_total','employer_survey_total'),
                'Coefficients'=c(dan_all$coefficients))
avg_intercept <- intercepts$Coefficients[[1]]+intercepts$Coefficients[[2]]*mean(all_metrics$Disposition_highest_level) + intercepts$Coefficients[[4]]*mean(all_metrics$self_survey_total)+intercepts$Coefficients[[5]]*mean(all_metrics$employer_survey_total)
all_chart <- ggplot(drop_na(all),aes(x=Prax_avg_zscore,y=WDanielson_highest_level)) + geom_point() 
for (row in c(1,2,3,5,6)) {
  all_chart <- all_chart + geom_abline(intercept=intercepts$Coefficients[[row]],
                                  slope=intercepts$Coefficients[[4]])
}
all_chart

## Comparing the metrics

In this piece, we'll start comparing across different metrics of teacher success.

+ The Disposition score of the student's most important college class (modified using the same z-score method as Danielson)
+ Whether or not they received Idaho teacher certification
+ How well the student did on their Praxis exams relative to their peers (not just if they passed, but by what margin)
+ Surveys from the principal, evaluating that student's effectiveness in the classroom as a teacher
+ Surveys from the student themselves with the same questions.

```{r, warning=FALSE}
library(tidyverse)
library(arrow)
library(ResourceSelection)
library(ggpubr)
library(pander)

all <- read_parquet("../../Scripts/All_teacher_info.parquet") %>%
  filter(!is.na(WDanielson_highest_level)) %>%
  select(StudentID,WDanielson_highest_level,Disposition_highest_level,Prax_avg_zscore,certification,
         employer_survey_total,self_survey_total)

all %>%
  arrange(self_survey_total) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  head(5) %>%
  pander()
```

### Danielson & Z-Score 

This analysis builds off the aggregation of Danielson observations recorded in [this article](https://sites.google.com/view/benjamin-pacini/dissertation/data-overview/danielson-fft?authuser=0).<br> In summary, we've condensed down the Danielson observations across dozens of classes and individual reports based on three criteria:

1.  We've prioritized observations from the classes furthest along in the student's career. For most students, we use their scores from ED 492, but for those missing observations, we use any other 400-level, then 300- and 200-level class.
2.  If a student has more than one observation recorded for the class, we prioritize the summative evaluations over the formative ones.
3.  To compensate for different grading standards across teachers, we've turned each raw final score (a 3-pt scale of 22 questions) into a z_score. Now each score reflects how the student did in this class compared to their peers.-

$$
zscore = \frac{x_{StudentScore} - \mu_{TeacherAndSemester}}{\sigma_{TeacherAndSemester}}
$$ After these steps, we go from 9854 individual observations to 1776 values tied to student records.

Unfortunately, only 23 of our 1776 potential teachers received all 6 of these summative evaluations. As a result, each of these smaller analysis will use different sub-sections of these 1776 students.
<br>

It's important to notice that because we made all these adjustments from the raw observations, this analysis won't be useful for predicting individual scores. This can only tell which other metrics are most likely to help students succeed.

## Danielson against Disposition

These two features have a strong positive relationship. Many of these students were tested by the same teacher for both types of evaluation, so the correlation may be influenced by the same source.

```{r}
lm_dan_disp <- lm(WDanielson_highest_level ~ Disposition_highest_level, data = all)
summary(lm_dan_disp) %>% pander::pander()
```

```{r}
ggplot(all,aes(x=Disposition_highest_level,y=WDanielson_highest_level)) +
  geom_jitter() + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm') +
  labs(x='Disposition score for most relevant class',y='Adjusted Danielson score',
    title="Strong correlation between Disposition & Danielson") 
```

## Across all Metrics

As we wrap up, let's see what insights we can find as we pull all of these different metrics together. Unfortunately, only 23 students have all 6 of these metrics, which gives a very unlikely skew to our results.

```{r}
all_metrics <- drop_na(all) #now only the people with all metrics
dan_all <- lm(WDanielson_highest_level~Disposition_highest_level+certification+Prax_avg_zscore+self_survey_total+employer_survey_total,data=all_metrics)
summary(dan_all) %>% pander()
```

*Certification* disappears because all of these students were certified. In this subsample, only the praxis scores appear statistically significant, but they actually have an opposite effect: high-performing Danielson students are correlated with worse outcomes on Praxis. We can likely blame this on the small sample size.

```{r eval=FALSE}
intercepts = tibble('Factor'=c('Intercept','Disposition_highest_level','certification','Prax_avg_zscore','self_survey_total','employer_survey_total'),
                'Coefficients'=c(dan_all$coefficients))
avg_intercept <- intercepts$Coefficients[[1]]+intercepts$Coefficients[[2]]*mean(all_metrics$Disposition_highest_level) + intercepts$Coefficients[[4]]*mean(all_metrics$self_survey_total)+intercepts$Coefficients[[5]]*mean(all_metrics$employer_survey_total)
all_chart <- ggplot(drop_na(all),aes(x=Prax_avg_zscore,y=WDanielson_highest_level)) + geom_point() 
for (row in c(1,2,3,5,6)) {
  all_chart <- all_chart + geom_abline(intercept=intercepts$Coefficients[[row]],
                                  slope=intercepts$Coefficients[[4]])
}
all_chart
```
